## Understanding MITRE ATT&CK

The MITRE ATT&CK (Adversarial Tactics, Techniques, and Common Knowledge) framework is one of the most valuable resources for security professionals. It provides a comprehensive knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques based on real-world observations.

As a SOC Analyst at the National Center of Cyber Security, I use ATT&CK daily for threat detection, incident analysis, and building detection rules. In this guide, I'll share practical approaches to leveraging ATT&CK in SOC operations.

## The ATT&CK Matrix Structure

The framework is organized into three main components:

1. **Tactics** — The adversary's tactical goals (the "why")
2. **Techniques** — How the adversary achieves those goals (the "how")
3. **Procedures** — Specific implementations by threat actors

### Key Tactics

| Tactic | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| Initial Access | Gaining entry to the network | Phishing, exploiting public-facing apps |
| Execution | Running malicious code | PowerShell, command-line scripts |
| Persistence | Maintaining access | Registry run keys, scheduled tasks |
| Privilege Escalation | Gaining higher permissions | Token manipulation, exploitation |
| Defense Evasion | Avoiding detection | Obfuscation, disabling security tools |
| Credential Access | Stealing credentials | Keylogging, credential dumping |
| Discovery | Understanding the environment | Network scanning, file enumeration |
| Lateral Movement | Moving through the network | RDP, SMB, pass-the-hash |
| Exfiltration | Stealing data | Encrypted channels, cloud storage |
| Impact | Disrupting operations | Ransomware, data destruction |

## How I Use ATT&CK in SOC Work

### 1. Threat Detection

Every detection rule I write maps to at least one ATT&CK technique. This ensures comprehensive coverage and helps identify gaps:

```yaml
# Example Wazuh rule mapped to ATT&CK
# Technique: T1059.001 (PowerShell)
# Tactic: Execution

rule:
  id: 100100
  level: 12
  description: "Suspicious PowerShell execution detected"
  mitre:
    tactic: Execution
    id: T1059.001
    technique: "Command and Scripting Interpreter: PowerShell"
  match:
    - "powershell.exe -encodedcommand"
    - "powershell.exe -enc"
    - "powershell.exe -e "
```

### 2. Incident Analysis

When analyzing an incident, I map observed activities to ATT&CK techniques to build a complete picture of the attack:

```
Incident Timeline (ATT&CK Mapped):

1. T1566.001 (Phishing: Spear-phishing Attachment)
   → User opened malicious PDF attachment

2. T1059.001 (PowerShell)
   → Payload executed via PowerShell

3. T1547.001 (Registry Run Keys)
   → Persistence established via registry modification

4. T1003.001 (LSASS Memory)
   → Credential dumping via Mimikatz

5. T1021.001 (Remote Desktop Protocol)
   → Lateral movement to server via RDP

6. T1048.003 (Exfiltration Over Unencrypted Protocol)
   → Data exfiltrated via HTTP
```

