## Integration with SIEM Platforms

### Wazuh Integration

Wazuh natively supports MITRE ATT&CK mapping in its rule engine:

```xml
<rule id="100200" level="10">
  <if_sid>60106</if_sid>
  <field name="win.eventdata.commandLine">
    certutil\.exe.*-urlcache
  </field>
  <description>Certutil used for file download (T1105)</description>
  <mitre>
    <id>T1105</id>
  </mitre>
</rule>
```

### Splunk Integration

In Splunk, I use the Enterprise Security framework with ATT&CK annotations:

```spl
| tstats count FROM datamodel=Endpoint.Processes
  WHERE Processes.process_name="powershell.exe"
  BY Processes.process_name Processes.process
| lookup mitre_attack_lookup technique_id AS process_technique
| table _time process_name technique_name tactic
```

## Threat Hunting with ATT&CK

ATT&CK-based threat hunting follows a hypothesis-driven approach:

1. **Select a technique** — e.g., T1003 (OS Credential Dumping)
2. **Form a hypothesis** — "An adversary may be dumping credentials via LSASS"
3. **Identify data sources** — Process creation logs, Sysmon events
4. **Build queries** — Search for indicators of the technique
5. **Analyze results** — Investigate any suspicious findings
6. **Document findings** — Update detection rules and playbooks

### Example Hunt Query

```spl
# Hunting for LSASS memory access (T1003.001)
index=sysmon EventCode=10 TargetImage="*lsass.exe"
| stats count by SourceImage, SourceUser
| where count > 1
| sort - count
```

